@gmr - thanks for the info, much appreciated!

I took your suggestion and moved the blocking function to be called in a separate thread so the IOLoop isn't blocked, and it seems to work great now.  I ended up using adding a `concurrent.futures.ThreadPoolExecutor` to my consumer.  So my solution looks something like:

```python
from rejected import consumer
from tornado import gen

class Consumer(consumer.Consumer):

    executor = ThreadPoolExecutor(4)

    @gen.coroutine
    def process(self):
        yield self.executor.submit(self.blocking_thing)

    def blocking_thing(self):
        self.logger.info('Starting the blocking sleep')
        time.sleep(30)
        self.logger.info('Done blocking sleep')
```

