It seems to me, that it's not really supported by flask to dynamically adjust routes at runtime so as far as I see it there is no way around restarting/reloading the server.

If someone has the same problem as me, maybe this'll help.

The way I solved the restart problem, was to run the flask app with another wsgi server that supports daemon mode (in my case gunicorn) and restart that by sending a HUP signal to the process. This doesn't work with the integrated server, since it's not running as a daemon and thus can't restart itself after it shut itself down. (Resulting in your app server just stopping)

    $ gunicorn --daemon app:app

and then have a route to restart the server

    @app.route('/restart-server/')
    def restart-server():
      os.kill(os.getpid(), signal.SIGHUP)

Which I then call via AJAX, so that I don't run into "could not load page" errors due to the server temporarily not being available.

    $ vi static/js/function.js
    function reload-server() {
      // Reload Server
      $.ajax({
        url: "/reload-server/"
      });
      // Wait 1 second and reload page
      setTimeout(function(){
        window.location = document.URL;
      }, 1000);
    }

And I call that with a simple button.

    <head><script src="/static/js/functions.js"></script></head>
    # wherever you want to put the button...
    <button onclick='reload-reload()'>Reload Server</button>

By theory you have to root all the Django traffic to Nginx and Nginx take care of the rest. Remember that nginx always running in the port 80 because of this you don't have to your Django server by port 80. 

- Case1. Please run Django as normal server `python manange.py runserver` Please see below example taken from gunicorn nginx settings...
```  
server {
    listen 80;
    server_name example.org;
    access_log  /var/log/nginx/example.log;

    location / {
        proxy_pass http://127.0.0.1:8000;
        proxy_set_header Host $host;
        proxy_set_header X-Forwarded-For $proxy_add_x_forwarded_for;
    }
  }
```
- Case2. Stop Nginx server so port 80 will be free and run Django as 

    python manage.py runserver 0.0.0.0:80

